{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504181"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:12:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:12:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2306"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2306"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.64,0.28,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2306"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67937"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"4862"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1262"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with community-acquired pneumonia. She has developed urinary incontinence over the past few days and has been using continence pads. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable. Her vital signs are within normal limits. There is a 4x4 cm ulcerated area over her sacrum with partial thickness skin loss involving the dermis. The ulcer base shows blistering but does not extend to underlying muscle, bone or fascia. The surrounding skin appears macerated from moisture exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate classification for this pressure ulcer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Grade 1 pressure ulcer","Grade 2 pressure ulcer","Grade 3 pressure ulcer","Grade 4 pressure ulcer","Unstageable pressure ulcer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a pressure ulcer showing partial thickness skin loss with dermis involvement and blistering, which are characteristic features of a \u003Cstrong\u003EGrade 2 pressure ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E. The presence of urinary incontinence and moisture exposure increases the risk of pressure ulcer development and progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EGrade 1 pressure ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E presents as non-blanchable erythema of intact skin, often with associated warmth, oedema or induration. The skin remains intact without ulceration, making this classification incorrect for this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EGrade 3 pressure ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E involves full thickness skin loss extending into the subcutaneous tissue but not through the underlying fascia. This patient\u0027s ulcer does not extend this deeply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EGrade 4 pressure ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E shows extensive destruction with damage to muscle, bone, or supporting structures. This degree of tissue damage is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eunstageable pressure ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E is one where the true depth cannot be determined due to the presence of slough or eschar. In this case, the wound bed is visible and can be accurately staged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe European Pressure Ulcer Advisory Panel (EPUAP) classification system helps guide appropriate management strategies. For Grade 2 ulcers, management focuses on pressure relief, moisture management, and maintaining a clean wound environment. The presence of incontinence requires particular attention to skin protection and moisture management to prevent further tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Grade 2 pressure ulcers involve partial thickness skin loss with dermis involvement, presenting as blisters or abrasions","Pressure ulcer grading guides management and allows monitoring of healing","Incontinence is a significant risk factor for pressure ulcer development and progression"],"references":["European Pressure Ulcer Advisory Panel and National Pressure Ulcer Advisory Panel. Prevention and treatment of pressure ulcers: quick reference guide. Washington DC: National Pressure Ulcer Advisory Panel; 2009.","Bluestein D, Javaheri A. Pressure ulcers: prevention, evaluation, and management. Am Fam Physician 2008; 78:1186.","Lyder CH. Pressure ulcer prevention and management. JAMA 2003; 289:223.","Wang C, Schwaitzberg S, Berliner E, et al. Hyperbaric oxygen for treating wounds: a systematic review of the literature. Arch Surg 2003; 138:272.","Pressure Injury Prevention and Management. NSW Health. Updated July 2021. Available from: https://www1.health.nsw.gov.au/pds/ActivePDSDocuments/PD2021_023.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67937"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2306"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67937"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T13:08:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T13:10:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2306"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82834"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}